n of realism fails to account for one of the most important components of these sagas, the abundance of skaldic poetry, mostly in dróttkvætt "court metre", which comes to saga heroes' lips at moments of crisis. These presumed voices from the past and their integration into the narrative present of the written sagas are the subject of this book. It investigates what motivated Icelandic writers to develop this particular mode, and what particular literary effects they achieved by it. It also looks at the various paths saga writers took within the evolving prosimetrum (a mixed verse and prose form), and explores their likely reasons for using poetry in diverse ways. Consideration is also given to the evolution of the genre in the context of the growing popularity in Iceland of romantic and legendary sagas. A final chapter is devoted to understanding why a minority of sagas of Icelanders do not use poetry at all in their narratives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn Icelandic.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSagasxHistory and criticism. 0aScalds and scaldic poetryxHistory and criticism. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aCourt metre.  aCrisis.  aFamily sagas.  aHistorical context.  aIceland.  aLegendary sagas.  aLiterary effects.  aNarrative.  aRealistic descriptions.  aRomantic sagas.  aSkaldic verse.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311143099740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781800106116?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800106116423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781800106116/original  a978-3-11-143099-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles